\name{covariateEffects}
\alias{covariateEffects}
\title{Summarize How Biological Predictors Affect Evolutionary Rates}
\description{
After fitting a model with covariates (e.g., body size, generation time,
habitat), this function tells you whether those predictors significantly
affect the rate of character evolution. For each predictor, you get the
posterior distribution of its effect, a credible interval, and a measure
of how confident we can be that the effect is positive or negative.

\strong{What does a positive or negative coefficient mean?}
\itemize{
  \item \strong{Positive coefficient}: Higher values of the predictor are
    associated with faster rates of character evolution. For example, if
    body size has a positive coefficient, larger-bodied lineages tend to
    evolve the character faster.
  \item \strong{Negative coefficient}: Higher values of the predictor are
    associated with slower rates.
  \item \strong{Coefficient near zero (credible interval overlaps zero)}:
    No detectable relationship between the predictor and evolutionary rate.
}

The coefficients describe the effect on \emph{log}-rate, so a coefficient
of 0.5 means that a one-standard-deviation increase in the predictor is
associated with a rate that is exp(0.5) = 1.65 times faster.
}
\usage{
covariateEffects(fit, burnin_frac = 0, prob = 0.95)
}
\arguments{
\item{fit}{A model fitted with covariates by \code{\link{fitRateScape}}.
If the model was fit without covariates, this function will produce an
error.}

\item{burnin_frac}{Fraction of additional burn-in to discard (0 to 1). The
main burn-in was already removed during fitting; this allows discarding
extra samples if the chain was slow to converge. Default 0 (use all
post-burn-in samples).}

\item{prob}{Probability level for the credible interval. Default 0.95
gives a 95\% credible interval. Use 0.90 for a 90\% interval.}
}
\value{
A data frame (printed to console and returned invisibly) with one row per
covariate and columns including:
\describe{
  \item{covariate}{Name of the predictor variable.}
  \item{mean_std}{Posterior mean of the coefficient on the standardized
    scale (predictors scaled to mean 0 and SD 1).}
  \item{lower, upper}{Lower and upper bounds of the credible interval
    (standardized scale).}
  \item{mean_orig}{Posterior mean on the original (unstandardized) scale.}
  \item{P_positive}{Posterior probability that the coefficient is positive
    (predictor increases rate).}
  \item{P_negative}{Posterior probability that the coefficient is negative
    (predictor decreases rate).}
  \item{significant}{Whether the credible interval excludes zero (i.e.,
    there is a clear directional effect).}
}
}
\examples{
\dontrun{
  # Full workflow: test whether body size predicts rate of diet evolution

  # 1. You have a tree and a diet character (0 = herbivore, 1 = carnivore)
  Q <- makeQ(model = "mk", k = 2)

  # 2. You also have body size measurements for each species
  body_sizes <- setNames(log(species_masses), tree$tip.label)

  # 3. Convert tip body sizes to edge-level covariates
  edge_sizes <- tipToEdgeCovariate(tree, body_sizes, method = "mean")

  # 4. Format as a matrix (can have multiple columns for multiple predictors)
  covars <- matrix(edge_sizes, ncol = 1)
  colnames(covars) <- "log_body_mass"

  # 5. Fit the model with covariates
  fit <- fitRateScape(tree, diet_data, Q, lambda_sigma = 1.0,
                       covariates = covars, ngen = 50000)

  # 6. Examine the covariate effects
  results <- covariateEffects(fit)
  # Example output:
  #   covariate     mean_std  lower   upper   P_positive  significant
  #   log_body_mass  0.420    0.081   0.759   0.990       TRUE
  #
  # Interpretation: Body size has a significant positive effect on diet
  # evolution rate. Larger-bodied lineages tend to have faster rates of
  # diet transitions.

  # For multiple predictors, add more columns:
  gen_time <- setNames(species_generation_times, tree$tip.label)
  edge_gen <- tipToEdgeCovariate(tree, gen_time, method = "mean")
  covars2 <- cbind(log_body_mass = edge_sizes,
                    generation_time = edge_gen)
  fit2 <- fitRateScape(tree, diet_data, Q, lambda_sigma = 1.0,
                        covariates = covars2, ngen = 50000)
  covariateEffects(fit2)
}
